> You can move the resource allocation from __init__ to __enter__, but now you split your initialization code over 2 constructors<p>After giving it some thought, I&#x27;ve come up with a better example which more closely maps to C++ RAII constructs, which shows that you don&#x27;t need to split anything. Consider:<p><pre><code>    class Shadow(object):
        def __init__(self):
            # Initialization code
        @classmethod
        def __enter__(cls, *args, **kwargs):
            return cls(*args, **kwargs)
        def __exit__(self, *args, **kwargs):
            # De-initialize
</code></pre>
`__enter__` becomes three lines of boilerplate, which you could abstract out into an inheritable class, should you so desire.<p>As for &quot;In C++ you write&quot;, it&#x27;s the same as saying &quot;in Python you write __enter__ and __exit__&quot;, but instead of instantiating via `std::unique_ptr` you use `with`.
